<div class="references-small">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> The evidence for ballcourts among the <a href="/wiki/Hohokam" title="Hohokam">Hohokam</a> is not accepted by all researchers and even the proponents admit that the proposed Hohokam ballcourts are significantly different from Mesoamerican ones: they are oblong, with a concave (not flat) surface. See Wilcox's article and photo at end of this article.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Schwartz.</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> The primary evidence for female ballplayers is in the many apparently-female figurines of the Formative period, wearing a ballplayer loincloth and perhaps other gear. In <i>The Sport of Life and Death</i>, editor Michael Whittington says: "It would [therefore] seem reasonable that women also played the game -- perhaps in all-female teams--or participated in some yet to be understood ceremony enacted on the ballcourt." (p. 186). In the same volume, Gillett Griffin states that although these figurines have been "interpreted by some as females, in the context of ancient Mesoamerican society the question of the presence of female ballplayers, and their role in the game, is still debated." (p. 158).</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> There is wide agreement on game originating in the tropical lowlands, likely the Gulf Coast or Pacific Coast: see e.g. Shelton, p. 109-110.</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> See Taladoire (2001) pp. 107-108.</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> See Hill, Blake and Clark (1998); Schuster (1998).</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> Miller and Taube (1993, p.42)</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> These Gulf Coast inhabitants, the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Olmeca-Xicalanca&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Olmeca-Xicalanca (page does not exist)">Olmeca-Xicalanca</a>, are not to be confused with the <a href="/wiki/Olmec" title="Olmec">Olmec</a>, the name bestowed by 20th century archaeologists on the influential Gulf Coast civilization which had dominated that region three thousand years earlier.</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> Ortiz and Rodríguez (1999), pp.228–232, 242–243.</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> Diehl, p. 27. See also Uriarte, p. 41, who finds that the juxtaposition at El Manati of the deposited balls and serpentine staffs (which may have been used to strike the balls - see Ortíz C, 1992) shows that there was already a "well-developed ideological relationship between the [ball]game, power, and serpents."</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> Ortíz and Rodríguez (1999, p.249); see also Ortiz, Rodríguez, and Delgado (1992) which investigates this relationship, as cited in the foregoing paper.</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> Diehl, p. 32, although the identification of a ballcourt within San Lorenzo has not been universally accepted.</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Bradley &amp; Joralemon,</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> Ekholm, p. 242.</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> Finca Acapulco, San Mateo, and El Vergel, along the Grijalva, have ballcourts dated between 900–550 BCE (Agrinier, p. 175).</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> Orr, p. 749.</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> Cohodas.</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> The 16th century Aztec chronicler <a href="/wiki/Toribio_de_Benavente_Motolinia" title="Toribio de Benavente Motolinia">Motolinia</a> stated that the games was played by a 2-man team vs. a 2-man team, 3-man team vs. a 3-man team, and even a 2-man team vs. a 3-man team (quoted by Shelton, p. 107).</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.calstatela.edu/academic/anthro/jbrady/ulama/photo3ab.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.calstatela.edu/academic/anthro/jbrady/ulama/photo3ab.htm" rel="nofollow">Cal State L.A.</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19" title="">^</a></b> Blanchard, p. 107, further citing Durán (1971:315-316).</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20" title="">^</a></b> Noble, p. 65.</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21" title="">^</a></b> Day, p. 66, who further references <a href="/wiki/Diego_Duran" title="Diego Duran" class="mw-redirect">Diego Duran</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bernardino_de_Sahag%C3%BAn" title="Bernardino de Sahagún">Bernardino de Sahagún</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22" title="">^</a></b> Shelton, p. 107-108, who quotes Motolinia.</li>
<li id="cite_note-23"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23" title="">^</a></b> Smith, p. 232.</li>
<li id="cite_note-24"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24" title="">^</a></b> Coe et al., p. 109.</li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire, 2003.</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26" title="">^</a></b> Scott, p. 54.</li>
<li id="cite_note-27"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27" title="">^</a></b> Dainzu gloves are discussed in Taladoire, 2003. See also Blanchard, p. 107.</li>
<li id="cite_note-28"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28" title="">^</a></b> Filloy Nadal, p. 22.</li>
<li id="cite_note-29"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29" title="">^</a></b> Schwartz states that the ball used by present-day players is 8 lbs.</li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30" title="">^</a></b> Filloy Nadal, page 30 as well as Leyenaar (2001) pp. 125-126.</li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31" title="">^</a></b> Coe et al., p. 109 or Cohodas, p. 259.</li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 98. Note that there are slightly over 200 ballcourts also identified in the <a href="/wiki/American_Southwest" title="American Southwest" class="mw-redirect">American Southwest</a> which are <i>not</i> included in this total, since these are outside Mesoamerica and there is significant discussion whether these areas were used for ballplaying or not.</li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33" title="">^</a></b> Quirarte, p.209-210.</li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 100. Note that Taladoire is measuring the "playing field", while other authors include the benches and other trappings (e.g. see Quirarte, pp. 205-208). Interestingly enough, it is thought that neither the Great Ballcourt nor Tikal's Ceremonial Court were used for actual ballgames (Scarborough, p. 137).</li>
<li id="cite_note-35"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35" title="">^</a></b> Day, p. 75.</li>
<li id="cite_note-36"><b><a href="#cite_ref-36" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire and Colsenet.</li>
<li id="cite_note-37"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37" title="">^</a></b> Kurjack, Maldonado C., Robertson.</li>
<li id="cite_note-38"><b><a href="#cite_ref-38" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 99.</li>
<li id="cite_note-39"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39" title="">^</a></b> Day, p. 69.</li>
<li id="cite_note-40"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 97.</li>
<li id="cite_note-41"><b><a href="#cite_ref-41" title="">^</a></b> Related by Santley, et al., p. 14-15.</li>
<li id="cite_note-42"><b><a href="#cite_ref-42" title="">^</a></b> See, for example, Taladoire and Colsenet ("We suggest that the ballgame was used as a substitute and a symbol for war.", p. 174), Fox, or Gillespie, who says that the ballgame was "a boundary maintenance mechanism between polities" (p. 340).</li>
<li id="cite_note-43"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43" title="">^</a></b> Kowalewski, et al., p. 43.</li>
<li id="cite_note-44"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44" title="">^</a></b> Santley et al., p. 14.</li>
<li id="cite_note-45"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45" title="">^</a></b> Day, p. 76, and Taladoire (2001) p. 114.</li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46" title="">^</a></b> Wilkerson, p. 59.</li>
<li id="cite_note-47"><b><a href="#cite_ref-47" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/California_State_University,_Los_Angeles" title="California State University, Los Angeles">California State University, Los Angeles</a>, Department of Anthropology, <a href="http://www.calstatela.edu/academic/anthro/jbrady/ulama/photohi.htm" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.calstatela.edu/academic/anthro/jbrady/ulama/photohi.htm" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48" title="">^</a></b> See, e.g., Kubler, p. 147 or Miller.</li>
<li id="cite_note-49"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49" title="">^</a></b> Maria Uriarte, p. 46.</li>
<li id="cite_note-50"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50" title="">^</a></b> Among other sources, see Schele and Miller, who say "It would not be surprising if the game were rigged", p. 249.</li>
<li id="cite_note-51"><b><a href="#cite_ref-51" title="">^</a></b> Cohodas, p. 255, or Gillespie, p. 321.</li>
<li id="cite_note-52"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52" title="">^</a></b> Schele and Miller, who state that "occasionally [sacrificial victims'] decapitated heads were placed in play", p. 243.</li>
<li id="cite_note-53"><b><a href="#cite_ref-53" title="">^</a></b> See Bradley, who finds that a raised circular dot, or a U-shaped symbol with a dot in the middle, or raised U- or V-shaped areas each represent maize.</li>
<li id="cite_note-54"><b><a href="#cite_ref-54" title="">^</a></b> The ball-as-sun analogy is common in ballgame literatureSee, among others, Gillespie, or Blanchard. Some researchers content that the ball represents not the sun, but the moon.</li>
<li id="cite_note-55"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55" title="">^</a></b> Cohodas, p. 255.</li>
<li id="cite_note-56"><b><a href="#cite_ref-56" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire and Closenet, p. 173.</li>
<li id="cite_note-57"><b><a href="#cite_ref-57" title="">^</a></b> Zender.</li>
<li id="cite_note-58"><b><a href="#cite_ref-58" title="">^</a></b> These excerpts from the Popol Vuh can be found in Christenson's recent translation or in any work on the Popol Vuh.</li>
<li id="cite_note-59"><b><a href="#cite_ref-59" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 109, who states that Matacapan and Tikal did indeed build ballcourts but only after the fall of Teotihuacan.</li>
<li id="cite_note-60"><b><a href="#cite_ref-60" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 112.</li>
<li id="cite_note-61"><b><a href="#cite_ref-61" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 112.</li>
<li id="cite_note-62"><b><a href="#cite_ref-62" title="">^</a></b> Taladoire (2001) p. 113.</li>
<li id="cite_note-63"><b><a href="#cite_ref-63" title="">^</a></b> The Nahuatl word for the game, <i>ōllamaliztli</i> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[o:llama'listɬi]</span>) was often spelled <i>ullamaliztl</i> - the orthography with "u" is a misrendering of the Náhuatl word caused by the fact that the quality of the nahuatl vowel /ō/ sounds a little like Spanish /u/.</li>
<li id="cite_note-64"><b><a href="#cite_ref-64" title="">^</a></b> Interestingly, the name of the present day city of <a href="/wiki/Taxco" title="Taxco">Taxco</a>, <a href="/wiki/Guerrero" title="Guerrero">Guerrero</a>, comes from the Nahuatl word <i>tlachcho</i> meaning "in the ballcourt".</li>
<li id="cite_note-65"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65" title="">^</a></b> De La Garza &amp; Izquierdo (1980) p.315.</li>
<li id="cite_note-66"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66" title="">^</a></b> Wilkerson, p. 45 and others, although there is by no means a universal view: Santley et al. say "The game was played by nearly all adolescent and adult males, noble and commoner alike." (p. 9)</li>
<li id="cite_note-67"><b><a href="#cite_ref-67" title="">^</a></b> Duran is quoted in Smith (2003), p. 233. <a href="/wiki/Toribio_de_Benavente_Motolinia" title="Toribio de Benavente Motolinia">Motolinia</a>, another early Spanish chronicler, also mentioned the heavy betting that accompanied games (Motolinia, p. 320).</li>
<li id="cite_note-68"><b><a href="#cite_ref-68" title="">^</a></b> De La Garza &amp; Izquierdo (1980) p.325.</li>
<li id="cite_note-69"><b><a href="#cite_ref-69" title="">^</a></b> Alegria.</li>
</ol>
